        </p> -->
    </axiom>


    <example xml:id="ex-population-growth">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_hthv4nzd">A country's population grows by 5% each year. So if the initial population is <m>P_0</m>, then after <m>t</m> years the population is <m>P=P_0 (1.05)^{t}</m>. How long does it take for the population to double?</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_m6p53uie">For doubling <m>2P_0=P_0 e^{rt}</m> so <m>2=e^{rt}</m> giving <m>\ln 2 = rt</m> and <m>t=\frac{\ln2}{0.05}\approx 13.86\text{ years}</m>. (At 5% the doubling time is <m>\approx 14</m> years; to double in 10 years <m>r\approx6.93\%</m>.)</p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-carbon-dating">
        <title>Carbon Dating and Half-Life</title>
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_pefpc6xx">
                Carbon-14 dating is a method for estimating the age of formerly living things. While alive, organisms take in Carbon-14; after death the Carbon-14 decays and is not replaced, so the remaining fraction indicates how long it has been since death.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_77dx44hu">
                If the amount of carbon at the beginning is <m>N_0</m>, after <m>t</m> years the amount remaining is <m>N = N_0\left(\tfrac{1}{2}\right)^{t/T_{1/2}}</m>, where <m>T_{1/2}</m> is the half-life. For Carbon-14, <m>T_{1/2}=5730</m> years. In other words, every <m>T_{1/2}=5730</m> years the amount of Carbon-14 in the sample decreases by one half.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_a9238bok">
                A sample of human bones contains 12.5% of the amount of Carbon-14 in the bones of a living human being. Estimate the age of the sample.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_393u0ciu">
                As 12.5% remain, we have <m>N=0.125N_0</m>. Using the decay formula, we get <m>0.125N_0=N_0\left(\tfrac{1}{2}\right)^{t/5730}</m>. Dividing by <m>N_0</m>, we have <m>0.125=\left(\tfrac{1}{2}\right)^{t/5730}</m>. 
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_rocf8jbo">    
                Take log with base 2 on both sides: <m>\log_2 0.125=\tfrac{t}{5730}\log_2(1/2)</m>, so
                <m>t=5730\dfrac{\log_2 0.125}{\log_2 (1/2)}</m>. Since <m>\log_2 0.125=-3</m> and <m>\log_2 (1/2)=-1</m>, we get <m>t=5730\times3=17190</m> years.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-pH-calculation">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_l42f0jwi">The pH scale in chemistry is based on logarithms. Given that <m>pH = -\log [H^+]</m>, determine the pH of a solution where <m>[H^+] = 3.2\times 10^{-4}</m>.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_jgoghj6c"><m>pH = -\log(3.2\times 10^{-4}) = -(\log 3.2 + \log 10^{-4}) = -(0.5051 - 4) = 3.49</m> (acidic solution)</p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-richter-scale">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_gu19ids3">The Richter scale measures earthquake intensity using <m>R = \log(I/I_0)</m>. If an earthquake is 1000 times more intense than the reference, what is its magnitude?</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_kog8tiie">Here <m>I/I_0 = 1000 = 10^3</m>, so <m>R = \log 10^3 = 3</m>. Magnitude = 3.0.</p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Practice and Application / Elaborate</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_f8r52h7x">
            <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 15 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_jo5jnngj">
            <alert>Objective:</alert> To apply logarithmic formulas to solve real-world problems.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_gnpk23sq">
            <alert>Learning Experience:</alert> Students work through problems involving pH calculation (<m>pH = -\log[H^+]</m> with <m>[H^+] = 3.2 \times 10^{-4}</m>), Richter scale (earthquake 1000 times more intense than reference), population growth (doubling time at 5% growth rate), and carbon dating (estimating age from remaining Carbon-14).
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_cz6l4vfy">
            <alert>Teacher's Role:</alert> The teacher monitors students, helping them connect the formulas to real-world meaning and emphasizing units and context.
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <exercises xml:id="exercises-log-real-exit">
        <exercise xml:id="auto_algae_double">
            <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_algae_p">
                Assume the number of algae in Lake Victoria doubles every week. 
                <ol>
                    <li xml:id="auto_p0fdmult">
                        <p xml:id="auto_a92ml8z9">
                            If today Lake Victoria is one quarter covered in algae, how long does it take until it is fully covered?                           
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_h4ccwk8o">
                        <p xml:id="auto_7edn4dqe">
                            If today Lake Victoria is 1% covered in algae, how long does it take until it is fully covered?                           
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <ol>
                    <li xml:id="auto_e2xbx304">
                        <p xml:id="auto_zzxkpuvs">If at the beginning X% are covered, after <m>n</m> weeks the coverage is <m>X \cdot 2^n</m>. So we want to find <m>n</m> such that <m>X \cdot 2^n = 100\%</m>, i.e., <m>2^n = \frac{100}{X}</m>. If <m>X=25\%</m>, then <m>2^n = 4</m>, so <m>n= \log_2 4 = 2</m> weeks.</p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_9015vzqa">(We can also see this directly: start at 1/4. After 1 week → 1/2; after 2 weeks → 1 (fully covered). So it takes 2 weeks.)</p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_elxc3h7q">
                        <p xml:id="auto_6hxdlx5z">
                            If <m>X=1\%</m>, then <m>2^n = 100</m>, so <m>n= \log_2 100</m>. Since <m>\log_2 100 = \frac{\ln 100}{\ln 2} \approx \frac{4.605}{0.693} \approx 6.64</m>, it takes approximately 6.64 weeks.                  
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_nmekryv7">2 weeks</p>
            </answer>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_14fz8i9f">Approximately 6.64 weeks</p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-investment-logarithm">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_e4cdvdj2">
                    You put 10000 ksh into an account that grows by 6% each year. How many years will it take for the money to double to 20000 ksh if the interest is added once per year?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_ovwmcege">
                    Each year, the new amount <m>A</m> of money is the old amount <m>P + 0.06 P = P(1 + 0.06) = P(1.06)</m>. So after <m>t</m> years, <m>A = P(1.06)^t</m>. Put <m>A=20000</m>, <m>P=10000</m>. So
                    <m>20000 = 10000(1.06)^t</m> which simplifies to <m>2 = 1.06^t</m>.
                    Take natural logs of both sides: <m>\ln 2 = t\ln 1.06</m>, therefore
                    <m>t = \dfrac{\ln 2}{\ln 1.06} \approx \dfrac{0.6931}{0.05827} \approx 11.9\ \text{years}.</m>
                    In plain terms: it takes about 12 years for the investment to double.
                </p>
            </solution>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_uecd5jhq">About 11.9 years (≈ 12 years)</p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="auto_newdecibel">
            <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_newdecibel_p">
                The sound level in decibels is given by <m>L = 10 \,\log_{10}\left(\frac{I}{I_0}\right)</m>, where <m>I_0 = 10^{-12}\,\text{W/m}^2</m> is a reference intensity. Calculate the decibel level of a sound whose intensity is <m>1.0 \times 10^{-3}\,\text{W/m}^2</m>.
            </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_nyha6f4q">Compute the ratio: <m>I/I_0 = 1.0\times10^{-3}/10^{-12} = 10^{9}.</m> Then <m>L = 10\log_{10}(10^{9}) = 10\times9 = 90\text{ dB}.</m></p>
            </solution>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_bxn4tkl1">90 dB</p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-newlogarithmicRate">
            <statement>
            <p xml:id="ex-newlogarithmicRate_p">
                The brightness of a star is measured on a logarithmic magnitude scale where a difference of <m>5</m> magnitudes corresponds to a brightness ratio of <m>100</m>. If one star is <m>250</m> times brighter than another, what is the difference in magnitudes between them? (Use logarithms.)
            </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_fbgh4sr2">If brightness ratio <m>R = 100^{\Delta m/5}</m>, then <m>250 = 100^{\Delta m/5}</m>. Take base-10 logs: <m>\log_{10}250 = (\Delta m/5)\log_{10}100 = 2(\Delta m/5)</m>, so <m>\Delta m = \tfrac{5}{2}\log_{10}250</m>. Using <m>\log_{10}250\approx 2.39794</m>, <m>\Delta m\approx(5/2)\times 2.39794\approx 5.9949\approx 6.0.</m></p>
            </solution>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_leov9mzn">Approximately 6.0 magnitudes</p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Assessment / Evaluate (Exit Ticket)</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_sd5jbvas">
            <alert>Objective:</alert> To formatively assess individual student understanding.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_seuslxy9">
            <alert>Learning Experience:</alert> Students complete exit ticket questions individually:
            <ol>
                <li xml:id="auto_q8ai201l"><p xml:id="auto_ix4edwyh">Research and describe two real-life applications of logarithms.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_0pvefcv6"><p xml:id="auto_zuzy7vp6">Determine the pH of a solution where <m>[H^+] = 3.2 \times 10^{-4}</m>.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_8kdia8f9"><p xml:id="auto_9r7va3ck">Find the Richter scale magnitude if an earthquake is 1000 times more intense than the reference.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_3w7rns8g"><p xml:id="auto_nq8660w5">Use logarithm tables to evaluate <m>\sqrt{(6.28 \times 42.5) / 9.81}</m>.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_uao6orrk"><p xml:id="auto_y2hwbrmy">Solve for <m>t</m> if a population doubles at a growth rate of 5% per year.</p></li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_7ofejtp9">
            <alert>Teacher's Role:</alert> Collect and review the exit tickets to gauge student understanding and identify any common misconceptions that need to be addressed in the next lesson.
        </p>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-checkpoint.ptx" />
    <xi:include href="../../resources-assessment.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>
        <tabular bottom="medium" top="medium" left="medium" right="medium">
            <row header="yes">
                <cell>Student Group</cell>
                <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Struggling Learners (Support)</cell>
                <cell>Scaffolding: Provide formula cards with examples. Focus on one application (pH or Richter). Use calculators for verification. Pair with stronger students during research.</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>On-Level Learners (Core)</cell>
                <cell>The core lesson activities as described above.</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</cell>
                <cell>Extended Learning Experience: 1) Research the decibel scale: If normal conversation is 60 dB and a rock concert is 120 dB, how many times more intense is the concert? 2) The half-life of a radioactive substance is given by <m>t_{1/2} = \ln(2)/\lambda</m>. If a substance has a half-life of 5 years, find its decay constant <m>\lambda</m>. 3) Create your own real-world problem using logarithms.</cell>
            </row>
        </tabular>
    </axiom>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Extended Learning Experience Solutions</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_mtxal2g9">
            <alert>1. Decibel Problem:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_ioqgiehb">
            <m>120 \text{ dB} - 60 \text{ dB} = 60 \text{ dB difference}</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_p0j1p8h9">
            <m>60 = 10 \log(I_2/I_1)</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_sey4ursb">
            <m>6 = \log(I_2/I_1)</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_zffcylri">
            <m>I_2/I_1 = 10^6 = 1{,}000{,}000</m> times more intense
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_ktwnxk18">
            <alert>2. Half-life Problem:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_jte0xedw">
            <m>t_{1/2} = \ln(2)/\lambda</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_ha1pyc9x">
            <m>5 = 0.693/\lambda</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_elp7u3mm">
            <m>\lambda = 0.693/5 = 0.1386</m> per year
        </p>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-reflection.ptx"/>

</subsubsection>
